Smart table simply add a isSelected = true to selected items following a given set of rules depending on the selection mode (and add a class on selected rows for styling purpose). Then you can do whatever  you want depending on your use case:
1.  creating watch on item basis
```Javascript
app.directive('selectNotifier', function(){
   return {
     scope:{
        row:'=',
        link:function(scope){
             scope.$watch('row.isSelected', function(value){
                // do what you want 
             })
        }
     }
   }
})
```

2. add your own event handler on the row
```Makrup
<tr st-select-row="row" ng-click="doSomething(row)></tr>
```

3. if it a bulk operation you want to do you can simply filter selected items when performing the action
```Javascript
$scope.doSomeStuffToSelected=function(){
   var selected = $scope.rowCollection.filter(function(item){
     return item.isSelected === true;
   })
   //do something with selected
}
``` 

4. globally enhance smart table controller
from a directive which require smart-table controller
```Javascript
var originalSelect = ctrl.select.bind(ctrl)
ctrl.select = function (row, mode) {
      originalSelect(row, mode)
       // do something else
}
```

actually this one could be easier if the controller.select returned the list of currently selected items

Anyway there is plenty of choices, you can even run you own selection code if you find it more convenient

Hi, thanks for the report and sorry for the late reply.

This is interesting and this whole backend is fairly janky. Your solution is certainly safer from a backwards compatability perspective but I'm not convinced it's the best way forward.

What do you think about instead doing the following:

```python
def _get_object(self, name):
    """Get object by its name. Raises libcloud.storage.types.ObjectDoesNotExistError None if object not found"""
    clean_name = self._clean_name(name)
    return self.driver.get_object(self.bucket, clean_name)

def exists(self, name):
    try:
        self._get_object(name)
        return True
    except ObjectDoesNotExistError:
        return False
```

And etc as we change the various methods to account for this. I don't think it really makes sense for `.size` to return -1 if the file doesn't exist, this is not a C library.

