that is a fantastic question, and I don't actually have a good answer. since with this specific example you don't have a way to see if the promise has resolved because it's in an anonymous scope.

this may not even be a good example.  currently, if you make a Promise, and that is what miniracer catches, then you would not have a way to check if that promise is done...
i suppose the better way of doing this would be to have a global var called done and to just check that untill everything has resolved?

so i suppose the code would look more like this:
```
var done = false;
var checkDone(){
    return done;
}
(function(){
    let thing = new Promise(function(resolve, reject){
            setTimeout(function(){
                    resolve()
                },1000)
            }),
    thing.then(r=>done=true)
})()
```

then i could simply do a while in python checking checkDone until it's done. that would let the event loop process things right?

