The simplest way to do this is probably to wrap code via a numpy transpose (which returns a view that simply references the original array's data with swapped strides/dimensions).  E.g. when returning from C++:

```C++
m.def("returns_matrix", []() {
    auto ret = py::cast(returns_matrix(), return_value_policy::move);
    return ret.attr("transpose")();
});
```

and, when going the other way:

```C++
using MyMatrixType = Eigen::Matrix<double, 3, Eigen::Dynamic>;
m.def("takes_matrix", [](py::array a) {
    takes_matrix(py::cast<MyMatrixType>(a.attr("transpose")());
});
```

(Assuming the `takes_matrix` function here takes an `Eigen::Ref` this would also avoid copying the data.)

